VALUES
(42, 8, 33, 66, 9, 11, 11, 'devils out of the man', 'Connection of Demonic Influence', 'This connection highlights the theme of demonic forces influencing both passages. In Luke, the devils enter the swine, while in Revelation, the king over the locusts is identified as an angel of the bottomless pit, suggesting a link between demonic activity and destruction.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 34, 41, 5, 14, 14, NULL, 'Connection of Fleeing Witnesses', 'Both passages emphasize the action of those who fed the swine fleeing and reporting what happened. This parallel highlights the immediate reaction to a significant event in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 34, 40, 8, 33, 33, 'they fled, and went', 'Fleeing and Reporting Events', 'Both passages emphasize the actions of those who tended the swine, highlighting their fear and subsequent decision to flee and report what had occurred. The similarity in their responses to the event underscores a shared narrative of shock and urgency.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 34, 40, 28, 11, 11, 'went and told it in the city', 'Reporting of Events', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals fleeing to report significant events. Both passages describe people who witnessed extraordinary occurrences and went to tell others in the city.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 34, 44, 19, 16, 17, 'they fled', 'Fear and Flight in Distress', 'Both passages emphasize the reaction of fear leading to flight. In Luke, those who witnessed the miracle fled to tell others, while in Acts, the men overcome by the evil spirit fled in fear after their encounter.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 35, 42, 10, 39, 39, 'sitting at the feet of Jesus', 'Sitting at Jesus'' Feet', 'This connection highlights the act of sitting at Jesus'' feet, which signifies a posture of learning and receiving. Both passages emphasize individuals who are transformed and engaged with Jesus, reflecting a state of peace and attentiveness.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 35, 19, 51, 10, 10, 'in his right mind', 'Transformation of the Mind', 'This connection highlights the theme of inner renewal. In Luke, the man is found ''in his right mind,'' paralleling the plea in Psalms for a ''clean heart'' and ''right spirit.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 35, 44, 22, 3, 3, 'sitting at the feet of Jesus', 'Sitting at the Feet', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''at the feet'' of a teacher or authority figure. In both passages, the act of sitting at the feet signifies a position of learning and transformation, whether from demonic possession to sanity or from zealousness to scholarly instruction.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 35, 62, 3, 8, 8, 'devils were departed', 'Deliverance from Evil', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' power over evil. In Luke 8:35, the man is freed from demons, while 1 John 3:8 states that Jesus was manifested to destroy the works of the devil.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 35, 23, 53, 12, 12, 'in his right mind', 'Healing and Redemption Connection', 'This connection highlights the transformation of the man in Luke, who is restored and in his right mind, paralleling the redemptive work described in Isaiah where the suffering servant bears the sin of many. Both passages emphasize the themes of restoration and intercession for those in need.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 35, 42, 8, 27, 27, NULL, 'Transformation of the Man', 'Both passages emphasize the drastic change in the man''s condition. In Luke 8:27, he is described as ''wearing no clothes'' and living among the tombs, while in Luke 8:35, he is found ''clothed, and in his right mind.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 35, 58, 2, 14, 15, 'in his right mind', 'Deliverance from Fear and Bondage', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance from demonic influence and fear. In Luke, the man is found ''in his right mind,'' indicating freedom from bondage, while Hebrews speaks of deliverance from the fear of death, which is linked to the devil''s power.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 36, 40, 4, 24, 24, NULL, 'Healing of the Possessed', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of those possessed with devils. Luke 8:36 recounts the healing of a specific individual, while Matthew 4:24 describes a broader context of healing for many, including those possessed.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 37, 44, 16, 39, 39, 'besought him to depart from them', 'Fear and Request for Departure', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear leading to requests for departure in both passages. In Luke, the Gadarenes ask Jesus to leave due to fear, while in Acts, the people beseech Paul and Silas to depart from the city.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 37, 5, 5, 25, 25, 'great fear', 'Fear of Divine Presence', 'This connection highlights the fear experienced by both the Gadarenes and the Israelites in the presence of divine power. In Luke, the multitude is ''taken with great fear,'' while in Deuteronomy, the people express fear of dying from the ''great fire'' and the voice of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 37, 9, 6, 20, 20, 'great fear', 'Fear of the Holy God', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in the presence of the divine. Both passages express a profound fear of God''s holiness, leading the people to desire separation from Him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 37, 11, 17, 18, 18, 'taken with great fear', 'Fear and Response to Prophets', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in response to divine encounters. In both passages, individuals express fear when confronted with the power of God through His prophets, leading to a desire for separation or departure.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 37, 18, 21, 14, 15, NULL, 'Fear and Rejection of God', 'This connection highlights a common theme of fear leading to a desire for separation from God. In both passages, the characters express a wish for God to depart due to their fear or rejection of His ways.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 37, 40, 8, 34, 34, NULL, 'Request for Jesus to Depart', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s fear and their request for Jesus to leave. In Luke, the multitude besought him to depart due to great fear, while in Matthew, the whole city asked him to depart from their coasts.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 37, 41, 5, 17, 17, 'to depart from them', 'Request for Departure', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s request for Jesus to leave their region due to fear. This connection highlights a shared response from the Gadarenes after witnessing a miraculous event.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 38, 19, 145, 3, 12, NULL, 'Praise and Declaration of Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of declaring God''s greatness and mighty acts. In Luke 8:38, the man desires to follow Jesus, who has performed a miraculous act, while Psalm 145 emphasizes the importance of speaking of God''s wondrous works and greatness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 38, 41, 5, 18, 20, 'besought him that he might be with him', 'Request to Follow Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the man''s desire to be with Jesus after being healed from demonic possession. In each account, he prays or besought Jesus to accompany him, highlighting his gratitude and longing for closeness with the healer.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 38, 44, 9, 13, 16, NULL, 'Divine Commissioning of Individuals', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals being chosen for specific missions by Jesus. In Luke, the man desires to follow Jesus after being healed, while in Acts, Saul is chosen to bear Jesus'' name despite his past. Both passages emphasize the transformative purpose God has for those He calls.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 38, 2, 12, 25, 27, NULL, 'Deliverance and Service Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance from evil and the subsequent call to service. In Luke, the man delivered from demons desires to follow Jesus, while in Exodus, the Israelites are instructed to remember their deliverance and serve God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 38, 2, 13, 8, 9, NULL, 'Deliverance and Testimony', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance from oppression. In Luke, the man freed from demons desires to follow Jesus, paralleling the Exodus passage where the Israelites are instructed to remember their deliverance from Egypt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 38, 5, 10, 20, 21, 'that he might be with him', 'Fear and Service to God', 'This connection highlights the theme of devotion to God. In both passages, there is an emphasis on serving and cleaving to God, as seen in the request of the man in Luke and the directive in Deuteronomy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 38, 19, 27, 4, 4, NULL, 'Desire to Dwell with God', 'This connection highlights the man''s desire to be with Jesus, paralleling the psalmist''s longing to dwell in the house of the Lord. Both passages emphasize a yearning for closeness to the divine.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 39, 42, 17, 15, 18, 'shew how great things God hath done unto thee', 'Gratitude and Witness', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of returning to give thanks and share what God has done. The healed man in Luke 8:39 and the Samaritan in Luke 17:15-18 both express gratitude and proclaim God''s greatness.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 39, 54, 5, 8, 8, NULL, 'Providing for One''s Own', 'This connection highlights the importance of caring for one''s household. Both passages emphasize the responsibility to share the great things God has done, particularly within one''s own family or community.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 39, 5, 10, 21, 21, 'great things God hath done unto thee', 'Connection of God''s Great Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of proclaiming God''s great deeds. Both passages emphasize the importance of recognizing and sharing the significant actions God has performed.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
